Q1-3

park <- read_csv('http://www.dsi.uminho.pt/~pcortez/forestfires/forestfires.csv') %>%
  mutate(fire = ifelse(area > 0, 1, 0)) %>%
  mutate_at(.vars = vars(X, Y, fire, month, day), .funs = as.factor)

Q4

m <- svm(fire ~ ., data = select(park, -area), cost = 10, gamma = 0.1, kernel = "radial")

Q5

plot(m, park, temp ~ wind)

Q6

mutate(park, yhat = predict(m),
       err = yhat != fire) %>%
  summarize(accuracy_m = mean(!err))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   accuracy_m
##        <dbl>
## 1      0.946

Q7

The plot makes it seem like our svm model is pretty useless as every observation, regardless of the wind or temp, is being classified as a 0, that is, having no fire. However, the accuracy shows that the accuracy of the model is actually quite high of about 95%, which leads me to believe that the predictors of wind and temperature are not important in determining whether there is a fire, as the cross-section of the two predictors as shown in the plot does not show any separation between observations that are predicted to have fires versus those without.
